{"/service/ndnp/ndhi/batch_ndhi_ferengi_ver01/data/sn85042243/00383345959/1930122401/1094.xml":{"full_text":"THE BISMARCK TRIBUNE =?i^\nESTABLISHED 1873\nCity Ready For Gala Christmas\nMandan Women Sau Indians \u2018Beat Them Up\u2019\nMULT CONKED\nWITH BANK ROBBERY\nCASE, CLAM MADE\nOne Had Signed Complain\nCausing Arrest of Four\nSioux County Men\nSEARCHING FOR ASSAILANTS\nTwo Women Knocked Uncon'\necious but Do Not Suffer\nSerious Injuries\nSearch for two men reported to\nhave beaten Miss Marie Streltmatter\nend her companion, Freda Morant, In\nthe former\u2019s home at Mandan was\ncontinued today by Morton county\nauthorities who said they had uncov\nered no definite clue as to the men\u2019s\nIdentity.\nMiss Streltmatter told police the\ntwo men which she said were Indians,\nthreatened her because she had given\nauthorities Information which led to\nthe arrest of Sheriff John Gates of\nSioux eounty; his deputy, Joe Wicks;\nKenneth McDonald, and A. R. Nord\non charges of bank robbery. The\nwomen received superficial facial\nbruises, but otherwise appeared to\nhave suffered no 11! effects.\n***imaajxMpQcUA the two man\nentered the home and told\nBtnfttmatter, \u201cYou bettor quit trying\nto got those fellows into the peniten\ntiary, or you\u2019ll be killed,\u201d according\nto Connolly. Connolly said the wom\nen told him the men beat them after\nmaking the threats.\nMiss Streltmatter was beaten first,\nand when Miss Morant attempted to\ntelephone police, she too was beaten,\npolice said. Both women were\nknocked unconscious before the men\nleft and reported to police as soon as\nthey revived.\nQUAKE DESTROYS\nARGENTINE TOWN\nMany Inhabitants of La Poma,\nCapital of Salta, Are\nReported Killed\nSalta, Argentina, Dec. 24.\u2014OP) \u2014The\ntown of La Poma was reported de\nstroyed by an earthquake early today.\nThe authorities here organised a re\nlief expedition which left this morn\ning. The quake was felt strongly in\nSalta and there was some panic\namong the inhabitants.\nLa Poma is a small town in the\nAndes only a short distance from\nJSalta. This city is the capital of the\nstate of Salta, in northwestern Argen\ntina. The report from La Poma said\nmany of the inhabitants had been\nkilled.\nGETS CHRISTMAS DIVIDEND\nDenver, Dec. 24.\u2014 UP) \u2014A $9,000,000\nChristmas dividend by the Midwest\nRefining company is going mostly in\nto one exchequer. The Standard Oil\nCompany of Indiana owns 99.93 per\ncent of Midwest, which nas declared\nan extra dividend of sl4 a share.\nGrant County Said\nTo Be \u2018Best of Best\u2019\nPointing to its more than a\nmillion acres of fertile land, its\nabundant vein of lignite coal, its\nunusual success in growing all\ntypes of corn, and its fast-grow\ning livestock and dairy business,\nGrant county claims to be not\nonly the \u201cbest of the west\u201d but\nalso the \u201cbest of the best.\u201d\nOrganized in 1916, Grant\ncounty has developed rapidly.\nGrowing of Holstein cattle, swine,\nand poultry has taken a firm\nroot there. Grant farmers are\ncutting down on small grain pro\nduction in the interest of more\nand better diversification.\nSeventy-five per cent of the\ncounty\u2019s cattle are of the Hol\nstein in breed. More than 68\nper cent of all cattle in tlie\ncounty have been tested for tu\nberculosis, which has made out\nside demand for Grant county\ncattle large.\nThe Tribune today is publish\ning a story dealing with Grant\ncounty, which is another of the\nseries which this newspaper has\nbeen printing dealing with Mis\nsouri Slope localities. The Grant\nstory is printed on page 3.\nTHE STAR OF BETHLEHEM\n(An Editorial)\nThe Star of Bethlehem shines tonight over the homes of Bis-\nmarck. North Dakota, America and the world.\nEverywhere hearts and minds are being lifted up to who\ncame into the world a child and taught the greatest lessons human\nity knows today.\nTo 1 i ht> by millions of firesides, little stockings are being hung\nIn implicit confidence that they will be filled when morning cornea.\nas 1,900 years ago over the hills of Judea, the heavens\nring with the song On earth peace to men of goodwill.\u201d\nTonight the season of giving, of friendship and fellowship, love\nai KKiklndness reaches its peak. It is Christmas again and, in tribute\nwas **2? L n a man *er, the great and the humble, the\nrich and the poor, the fortunate and the unfortunate, mingle their\nexpressions of praise and thanksgiving.\nAnd, bright and clear, the Star of Bethlehem shines Just as of\nold, bringing peace to every heart, understanding to every mind.\nEveryone wishes Merry Christmas to his friends and the world.\nHe Is poor, indeed, who cannot find It ln his heart to say \u201cMerrv\nChristmas\u201d with entire honesty of heart.\nIn line with the spirit of the times and because it really means\nwhat it says, The Tribune takes this opportunity to extend the sea\nsons greetings to its subscribers and friends.\nIt wishes everyone a Merry Christmas and hopes that everv\none will feel the glow of the Star of Bethlehem.\nNelson Sauvain Elected\nState Board\u2019s Chairman\nNew Member Wine Over W. J.\nChurch in Organization\nMeeting\nNelson Sauvain, Devils Lake, newly\nappointed member of the state board\nof administration, was chosen chair\nman of the board at a reorganization\nmeeting Tuesday.\nSauvain was appointed by Gov.\nGeorge F. Shafer Monday to fill the\neacaoey left>by resignation of J. E,\nDavis, former chairman.\nThe meeting was brief with the five\nmembers of the board present. Three\nballots were taken, but Sauvain did\nnot participate in the voting. On the\nfirst two ballots the was two and\ntwo for Shuvaln and W. J. Church,\nfor five and a half years a member\nof the board. On the third ballot,\nthe vote was three for Sauvain and\none for Church.\nThe deadlock was broken when\nChurch cast his vote with Joseph A.\nKitchen, secretary of agriculture and\nlabor, and Bertha R. Palmer, super\nintendent of public instruction, in fa\nvor of Sauvain. R. B. Murphy sup\nported Church on every ballot, but\nafter Sauvain received the majority\nvote Murphy moved to make the elec\ntion unanimous.\nSauvain took the oath of office\nMonday after his appointment had\nbeen announced. Davis resigned last\nweek to devote himself to his business\nenterprises.\nHEARING FOR JOHN\nHOLMES POSTPONED\nCounsel for Wing Blacksmith,\nCharged With Murder,\nAsks Continuance\nPreliminary examination for John\nHolmes, Wing blacksmith charged\nwith the murder of George Piepkom,\nBurleigh county deputy sheriff, was\ncontinued until January 5 after a\nhearing before Justice of the Peace\nAnton Beer here Tuesday.\nCounsel for Holmes asked for con\ntinuance in order to subpoena sever\nal witnesses. Holmes last night was\ntaken to Washburn and placed in\nthe McLean county Jail. Until today\nHolmes was kept in a local hospital\nunder guard.\nTURKEY DINNERS CHEAP\nBed alia, Mo., Dec. 34.\u2014 </Ph-' Turkey\ndinners, a dime each! Fred Kueck\nserved 2,227 at his cafe. The fixin's\nIncluded cigars and near beer.\nCounty Attorney Overrules Judge and\nHealth Officials to Let Dance Go On\nAmarillo, Texas, Dec. 24.\u2014 m\nTwo days before Christmas all\nover the floor, the dancers were\nshuffling to the tune of a snore.\nTwas a marathon dance 12 days\non its way, with six weary couples\ndetermined to stay. Then all of a\nsudden, a writ held before, Mayor\nErnest O. Thompson dashed in\nthrough the door.\n\u201cAvast there,\u201d he shouted, Tis\ntime to disband; it\u2019s all (he writ\nI\u2019ve got here in my hand.\u201d\nThe steppers aU scattered with\nslow, measured tread, said one:\n\u201cI\u2019m glad, for full soon I\u2019d be\ndead.\n\u201cYou can\u2019t trip my trippeft,\u201d\nthe promoter protested. \u201cYes, 1\ncan,\u201d said the Mayor, \u201cI\u2019ll have\nyou arrested.\u201d So straight the\npromoter got out an injunction,\nand on went the dancers perform\ning their function.\nDOCTOR CONFERENCE\nPLANNING CAMPAIGN\nAGAINST MENU\n\u2022DiMjtM Which- Caused Three\nf Deaths in 1924 Has Caused\nSixty-nine This Year\nPlans for a concerted attack on\ncerebrospinal meningitis which Is\ntaking an increasingly heavy toll of\nNorth Dakota lives were formulated\nat a conference of phy/icians here\nTuesday at the offices of the state\nhealth department.\nTwenty physicians and others\nmapped out a plan of procedure for\ncombating the disease at the state\ntraining school, Mandan, and else\nwhere in the state. The need for\nthis action. Health Director A. A.\nWhittemore said, is shown by the\nfact that eight cases at Mandan have\ncaused three deaths and that deaths\nfrom the disease in North Dakota has\nIncreased from three in 1924 to 52 in\n1929 and 69 for 1930 up to December\n15*\nThe department took throat cul\ntures from aU children and employes\nat the training school Monday\nthis afternoon was to get a report\nfrom A. W. Ecklund, bacteriologist,\nwho has charge of that phase of the\nwork. Although the work at pres\nent is being concentrated in an ef\nfort to clear up the situation at the\nstate training school. Dr. Whitte\nmore said the condition there is not\nparticularly alarming, although it is\nthe only state institution from which\nthe disease has been reported.\nHave Been Examined\nOn five different occasions both\nstudents and staff have been examin\ned by taking cultures and no \"posi\ntive reactions\u201d have been found. Dr.\nWhittemore said. He believes one\ntrouble may be that the germs die\nbetween the time the cultures are\ntaken and the time they are placed in\nan Incubator in the state laboratory\nhere. To meet this situation the\nlaboratory equipment was m#ved to\nMandan Monday afternoon and the\ncultures placed in the Incubator as\nsoon as they were taken. Results of\nthis method remain to be ascertained.\nThe object of the meeting Tuesday\nwas to review the situation and con\nsider improvements in methods of\nascertaining presence of the disease.\nThe conferees agreed that the disease\nis spread by carriers, temporary or\n(Continued on page eleven\u00bb\nTo the health office chiefs the\nmayor then ran, and they looked\nup the law, and they got out a\nban. \"These girlies are working\ntoo hard and too long; they\u2019re be\ning mistreated, and that\u2019s very\nwrong.\u201d Thus ran the order\nand once more the feet stopped\nscouring the hardwood with\nrhythmic beat,\nBut the county attorney, by\nname Leo. Sparks, heard tell of\nthe battle and made some re\nmarks. He ordered the dance\nman released by the law, took the\nbit in his teeth and thrust out hie\njaw. \u201cThere\u2019s no legal basis for\naction like this; it\u2019s justice mis\ncarried. and the charge I\u2019ll dis\nmiss.\nSo with tears in their eyes and\ncorns on their toes, the dancers\nresumed with the wailing of\nwoes.\nBISMARCK, NORTH DAKOTA, WEDNESDAY, DECEMBER 24, 1930\nFIVEBILUON-DOLLAR\nEXPENDITURES PLAN\nTHROfIGHOUT NATION\nChallenges to Unemployment\nAre Made in All Sections\nof Country\nROAD FUNDS ARE INCREASED\nHighway Construction and Pub\nlic Works Being Pushed\nIn Middle West\nNew York, Dec. 24.\u2014 (JPh-A five\nbillion dollar construction symphony\nof chisels on stone, air hammers on\nsteel and pick and shovel on hard\nwinter earth Is the nation\u2019s challenge\nto unemployment.\nRoads that ordinarily would wait\nfor spring are pushing forward ln a\npay-envelope drive over the face of\nthe country, and steel and brick are\nmounting skyward in municipalities,\naccording to year-end reports com\npiled from all areas.\nOil pipe lines are stretching from\nthe southwest, new rails are glinting\nunder the Texas sun and public\nworks are dotting the states. At the\nsame time, demands for immediate\nrelief are being met with national,\nstate, municipal and private aid.\nThe country is a network el com\nmissioner and committees p\u2014\nforward every bit of public work pos\nsible and preventing suffering\nthose who cannot be put to work.\nThe network begins with the presi\ndent\u2019s emergency committee, headed\nby Colonel Arthur Woods, and\nbranches through the states and into\nthe smallest of communities with re\nlief organization.\nThe federal government plans\n$724,000,000 worth of building in the\nnext 12 months and for immediate\nexpenditure congress has Just appro\npriated $116,000,000, not including the\n$45,000,000 voted for drought relief.\nTotal Figure Is Large\nL. Seth Schltman, chief Statistician\nfor the F. W. Dodge corporation, es\nContinued on oage eleven)\nREDISCOUOTRATEOF\nTWOPERCENTISSET\nNew York Federal Reserve Bank\nAnnounces Lowest Rate\nIn World\nNew York, Dec. 24.\u2014<\u00a3>) \u2014a redis\ncount rate of 2 per cent\u2014the lowest\nin the history of the federal reserve\nsystem and the lowest in the world\u2014\nwent into effect in the New York\nFederal Reserve bank today.\nThe announcement that the rate\nat which member banks might bor\nrow has been cut from 2<4 per cent\nwas construed by newspapers as a\nstimulus to business revival and a\nmark of confidence in the nation\u2019s\ncondition.\nBankers were quoted as saying the\nfederal reserve\u2019s action in inviting\nmember banks to avail themselves\nfreely of its credit was the most con\nstructive move possible, in view of\nthe widespread disturbances in the\nbanking field.\nIn addition, Wall Street opined, the\nreduction would renew fa*th abroad\nin the strength of the New York\nmoney market.\nYesterday\u2019s reduction was the\nseventh since the break in the stock\nmarket in the fall of 1929, when the\nrate was 6 per cent. At the present\ntime, the rate of the of France\nis 2*4 per cent and that of the Bank\nof England 3 per cent.\nBishop Wehrle Will\nSay Midnight Mass\nCelebration of midnight mass will\nbe the outstanding event of the\nChristmas services at St Mary pro\ncathedral, Rev. Father John A. H.\nSlag, rector, said today.\nThe ceremony will consist of a\npontifical high mass with Rt. Rev.\nVincent Wehrle, bishop of Bismarck,\nas celebrant. Bishop Wehrle also\nwill give the sermon.\nOther masses on Christmas day will\nbe said at 8,9, 10, and 11 a. m. The\nchildren will sing their Christmas\nsongs at the 9 o'clock mass.\nThe mass at 11 a. m. will be a high\nmass. All others, except the mid\nnight mass, will be low masses. The\nsermon at 11 a. m. will be given by\nFather Slag.\nThe St. Mary\u2019s male choir will sing\nat the midnight mass and again at\nthe 11 o\u2019clock mass. At the latter\nmass the men will be assisted bv the\nboys\u2019 choir.\nANNA KUMMER HAS\nBEGUN PRISON TERM\nTo Serve 18 Years in Peniten\ntiary for Killing Father\nat Anamoose\nMiss Anna Marie Kummer, 21,\nAnamoose, sentenced to 18 years for\nkilling her father, was in the state\npenitentiary today to begin her term*\nPrison officials said she will be as\nsigned to sewing and general house\nwork. Besides Miss Kummer there\nare four other women serving prison\nterms.\nGeorge Brown, state transportation\nofficer, brought the girl from Towner\nto the prison. At the same time he\ntook to prison Charles Hlgley, elderly\nGranville man, who was sentenced to\ntwo and a half years on an arson\ncharge.\nThe young woman had been in\njail at Towner since being sentenced\nearlier this month. Between the\ntime she was convicted and sentenced,\nseveral days, she preferred to remain\nat the sheriff\u2019s residence in Towner\nrather than return to Anamoose.\nToday State Transportation Officer\nBrown returned to Towner and was\nto bring to the penitentiary John\nMartin, under sentence of 15 years\nfor manslaughter; Robert E. Imette,\nunder sentence of two years for li\nquor offenses; and John McNamara,\nunder sentence of one and one-half\nyears on a statutory charge.\nBANNON TRIAL MAY\n(HE IN JANUARY\nJudge Lowe Informe Authorities\nHe Will Convene Court at\nTheir Desire\nMinot, N. D., Dec. 24.\u2014 OPh- District\nJudge John C. Lowe of Minot today\nannounced that he has advised State\u2019s\nAttorney J. 8. Taylor of McKenzie\ncounty that he will convene court\nanytime in January for the trial of\nJames F. Bannon, facing a charge of\nimplication in the slaying of the six\nmembers of the A. E. Haven family\nnear Schafer.\nIt is unlikely that the case will be\ntried in McKenzie county, Inasmuch\nas counsel for the defendant undoubt\nedly would ask for a change of venue,\naccording to McKenzie county of\nficials.\nIf a change of venue is made, Wil\nliston and Minot are considered the\nmost probable places for trial.\nBannon is making arrangements to\nemploy counsel.\nCUT BREAD PRICES\nNeenah, Wis., Dec. 24.\u2014<AP) \u2014A re\ntail price cut from 13 cents to 10 cents\nfor 24-ounce loaves of bread was in\neffect today. Bakers said low wheat\nprices made the reduction possible.\nExtra! Extra!\nT Christmases Expect\nI A Merry Christmas\nSuperior, Wls., Dec. 24.\u2014 (JP)\u2014\nIt will be a Merry Christmas in\nthe Christmas household when\nMary Christmas comes home for\nChristmas, William Christmas,\nher father, said today.\nAnd not only Mary, but Cedi\nChristmas and Mrs. Cecil Christ\nmas will join mother and father\nChristmas in the Christmas\nhome.\nSo also will Herbert A. Ronn,\nwho last year married Mary\nChristmas, so now there is no\nMary Christmas in the Christmas\nhome except at Christmas.\nMerry Christmas!\nBRAZILIAN INDIANS\nATTACK AMERICANS\n21 Employes of Ford Rubber\nPlantation at Cardosa\nReported Killed\nNew York, Dec. 24.\u2014<;p)\u2014A message\nfrom Para, Brazil, to Pan American\nAirways headquarters in New York\nsaid a Pan-American plane had been\nsent to the Ford rubber plantation, at\nthe request of the Brazilian govern\nment, on reports that there had been\ntrouble there with native laborers.\nThe plane left Para at 4 p. m. yes\nterday.\nAt the time the message was sent\nthere were reports at Para that no\nlives had been lost but that there had\nbeen considerable property damage.\nDispatches received at Rio de Jan\neiro last night said a band of Cayapos\nIndians had invaded the village of\nCardoso, in northern Para, killing 21\npersons and carrying three children\ninto the jungles.\nThe state government sent 30 sol\ndiers from Para but because of trans\nportation difficulties it was not be\nlieved they could reach Cardoso in\nless than eight days.\nUniverse Is Likened to Swelling Soap\nBubble Which Is Destined to Explode\nLondon, Dec. 24.\u2014(A*)\u2014The uni\nverse in which we live was likened\nto a fragile soap bubble by Sir\nJames Jeans, famous British\nscientist, in a radio lecture broad\ncast last night.\n\u201cIt is easy to blow a soap bub\nble,\u201d he said, \u201cbut far less easy\nto keep it in existence more than\na minute or two\u2014after that it is\napt to burst and disappear. I\nhope I shall not startle you too\nmuch if I say that it has been\ndiscovered quite recently the uni\nverse is somethign like that. As\nsoon as the universe came into\nexistence it started swelling and\nmust go on expanding.\u201d\nIf the calculations of many as\ntronomers as to the speed of\nCHAIN GROUP BUYS\nPRINCE HOTEL HERE\nLocal Hostelry to Be Taken Over\nby Roberts-McNab Firm\nJanuary 1\nPurchase of the Prince Hotel busi\nness by the Roberts-Mac Nab Hotel\ncompany was announced to The Trib\nune today by Arthur L. Roberts,\npresident.\nThe transfer from the present\nownership of E. A. Hughes wUI be\nmade January 1 and C. P. Stone will\nremain as manager, Mr. Roberts said\nin a telephone conversation.\nThe new owners have taken a 15-\nyear lease on the building, owner\nship of which is retained by Mr.\nHughes, and have purchased the\nfurniture, fixtures and other equip\nment.\nAcquisition of the Prince gives the\nRoberts Mac Nab company three ho\ntels in North Dakota. Others are\nthe Gladstone at Jamestown and the\nMayer at Devils Lake. In addition,\nthe company operates hotels in Min\nnesota, Wisconsin, Michigan, In\ndiana, Montana and Nebraska. Head\nquarters are at Winona, Minn.\nExpressing satisfaction that his\ncompany had been able to complete\nthe deal for the Prince, Mr. Roberts\nsaid he regards Bismarck as one of\nthe finest cities in the northwest\nwith unusually good prospects for fu\nture development.\nThe operation of the Prince, he\nsaid, will be kept on the same high\nstandard maintained under Mr.\nHughes\u2019 ownership.\n2 Children Burn to\nDeath in Kentucky\nBeals, Ky., Dec. 24.\u2014 (/P)\u2014 I Two chil\ndren were burned to death this morn\ning in a fire which destroyed the\nhome of Casper Goldsberry near here.\nCasper Goldsberry, Jr., three years\nold, and Mary Goldsberry, 18 months\nold, died in the flames.\nNebulae receding Is correct, he\nsaid, the universe must be ex\npanding\u201d\u2014l might almost say,\nexploding\u2014at a really terrific\nrate.\u201d\n\u201cThe material universe,\u201d he\ncontinued, \u201cappears to be passing\naway like a tale that\u2019s told, dis\nsolving into nothingness before\nthe light of day.\u201d\nHe said the number of stars\nprobably equaled the number of\nraindrops falling in London on\nthe days of a heavy rain, but that\nstill the universe was very empty.\n\u201cLeave only three wasps alive\nin the whole of Europe,\u201d he said,\n\u201cand Europe will be more crowded\nwith wasps than space with\nstars.\u201d\nPRICE FIVE CENTS\nNEEDYCAREDFORAS\nFAR AS POSSIBLE BY\nSEASONAL CAMPAIGN\nChurches Will Give Religious\nServices This Evening\nand Tomorrow\nCHRISTMAS DINNER PLANNED\nSanta Claus Talks to Children\nThis Aftsrnoon; Candy\nIs Distributed\nActivities in Bismarck took on a\ngala note today as Christmas eve ap\nproached.\nAgencies which have been Inter\nested ln caring for the unfortunate\nwere completing their work and the\nstreets and stores were filled with\nlast-minute shoppers.\nChurches of the city and county\nwere ready to present special services\ntonight and tomoa*ow and the spirit\nof \u201cOn earth peace to men of good\nwill\u201d was noticeably present.\nThe city\u2019s biggest p re-Christmas\ncelebration was that at the auditor\nium Wednesday afternoon ln which\nmore than 2,000 children participated.\nMembers of the Lions club dis\ntributed a bag of candy to each vis\nitor and had the Job of ushering the\nchildren and maintaining order dur\ning the program, which was arranged\nby the Rotary club. Boy Scouts as\nsisted the Lions ln ushering the hi\nlarious crowd.\nRev. F. E Logee of the Presbyter\nian church gave the invocation; Syl\nvia Benzon read the story of the na\ntivity, ar\u00bb<s Geotgf JHw\u00bbphrev\u00bb led\nthe children ln singing Christmas\ncarols. Mrs. R. E. Morris played the\npiano accompaniment.\nSanta Claus Appears\nSanta Claus appeared on the stage\nand talked to the children, telling\nthem some of his Innermost secrets.\nAs the children passed out of the\nauditorium they were presented with\nthe candy.\nThe American Legion had practic\nally finished its \u201cOpen Your Heart\"\ncampaign and only a few pairs -of\nold shoes remained at the headquar\nters on Main street. The last pack\nages were ready for delivery today\nand Milton Rue, campaign chairman,\n(Continued on page eleven)\nALLEGED ILLINOIS\nBANK ROBBERS HELD\nThree Men and Woman Arretted\nWhen $85,000 in Secur\nities Are Found\nChicago, Dec. 24.\u2014(J 5 )\u2014A police\nman's casual kick at a loose board in\na north side apartment revealed $85,-\n000 in stolen securities, police said,\nand caused the arrest of three men\nand a woman who are suspected by\nthe authorities of at least eight h*nk\nrobberies in central and northern Illi\nnois.\nTrailing a blue sedan with s\n\u201cwanted\u201d license number, Lieut. Andj\nBarry surprised Glen Nichols, 32, al\nleged Jail-breaker, and Gladys Rob\ninson, 27, Peoria, 111., and began a\ncursory examination of the apart\nment. A nick in the floor nwCnwg\nled to discovery of Liberty Bonds and\nnegotiable securities stolen, officials\nsaid, from the First State bank of\nWenona, the Allerton State bank and\nthe Farmers State bank at New\nWindsor.\nAustin J. Corray, 32, and his\nbrother Harmon, 27, who like Nichols\nare from Champaign, 111., later came\nto the apartment and were arrested.\nPolice said they confessed the three\nrobberies, implicating Nichols as the\nactual robber and the girl as the con\nfederate.\nSad Holiday Looms\nFor Orphaned Colt\nTaxi headquarters of the Yel\nlow Cab company were converted\ninto an improvised stable when\nJohn Haas, one of the company\ndrivers, discovered an orphaned\ncolt in the alley behind the of\nfices at 3 o\u2019clock thia morning.\nThe \u201cyoungster was discovered\nbeside the body of Its mother,\nwhich apparently had sought the\nseclusion of the alley to breathe\nher last.\nTurning the taxi headquarters\nInto a haven of refuge, Hhas\nsheltered the animn| \u2014tn g\no'clock this morning. At\njuncture, however, the colt almost\nwrecked the building when it\nrecognised fellow-equlnes gam\ning by drawing a loaded lea\nwagon.\nA dismol Christmas appeals la\nprospect for this motherless Bis\nmarck \"youngster.\u201d","height":"29136","width":"22479"}}
